<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-780-238  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 780 238.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Executive  Summer 1990 v3 n3 p32(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Networking at Indiana University.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Darragh, Thomas E.; Enyeart, Michael J.; Lindeman, Arthur J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Indiana University is working on integrating informationtechnologies with its instructional and research missions.andP;  IU has23 general access mainframe computers, 49 departmental mainframes,and over 6,000 microcomputers.andP;  The university is working onbringing all these together.andP;  The network has 5 layers: a campuslevel; a University level linking campuses; a state-wide levellinking public institutions and agencies; regional networks; andan interstate backbone.andP;  The departmental local area network isthe basis of the network.andP;  Novell Network supplies the distributedfile server and printer sharing services.andP;  Transmission ControlProtocol-Internet Protocol is used.andP;  The university is committedto the Fiber Distributed Data Interface for the Bloomington campusbackbone; it is also committed to Integrated Services DigitalNetwork.andP;  IU will adopt OSI standards when they become costeffective.andP;  Applications on the network include the librarycollections and an electronic school district.andP;  The university ismoving to automate network management and expects to useartificial intelligence to do so.andP;  Security on the network is setup to make authorized access very easy and unauthorized accessvery difficult.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     NetworksNetwork ManagementColleges and UniversitiesIndiana University.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographchart.andO;Caption:   Networking at Indiana University. (chart)The Indiana University Internet, also showing part of CICnet.andO;(chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>